         <div type="entry">
                <head>Abraham bar Dashandad</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Abraham-bar-Dashandad</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/21</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">12</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="7"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/317</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Nicknamed ‘the Lame of <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/1072">Beth Ṣayyade</placeName>’ after the
                        village in <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/993">Adiabene</placeName> were he was born, he was the disciple of the
                        reformer of ecclesiastical music <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/995">Babai of Gbilta</persName> and later
                        became teacher at the <orgName>School of
                            Bashosh</orgName> in <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/526">Persia</placeName>.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(8th <abbr>cent.</abbr>) [E.-Syr.]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Nicknamed ‘the Lame of Beth Ṣayyade’ after the village in <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Adiabene">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/993">Adiabene</placeName>
                        </ref> where he
                        was born, he was the disciple of the reformer of ecclesiastical music Babai
                        of Gbilta and later became teacher at the School of Bashosh in Persia,
                        founded by Babai, and the School of Marga. At the end of his life, he
                        established himself at the <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Gabriel-Monastery-of-Mor">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/226">Monastery of Mor Gabriel</placeName>
                        </ref> near <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Mosul">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/139">Mosul</placeName>
                        </ref>, known as the
                        Upper Monastery. According to <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Abdisho-bar-Brikha">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/310">ʿAbdishoʿ bar
                            Brikha</persName>
                        </ref>, he was the author of a Book of <choice>
                            <sic>a</sic>
                            <corr>A</corr>
                        </choice>dmonition, a Commentary of
                        Marcus Eremita, a Disputation with the Jews, a work on the Royal Path, some
                            <hi rend="italic">memre</hi> on penitence and different letters. Of the
                        latter, only his Letter to a certain Yoḥannan, who had decided to embrace
                        the monastic life, is preserved. It is followed by some spiritual
                        admonitions (<hi rend="italic">zuhhāre</hi>). His importance for Syriac
                        lexicography is acknowledged by <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Bar-Bahlul-Hasan">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/365">Bar
                        Bahlul</persName>
                        </ref>, who mentions him in the introduction to his Syriac-Arabic
                        lexicon. According to <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Timotheos-I">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/790">Timotheos I</persName>
                        </ref>, a
                        certain Abraham, who may have been Abraham bar Dashandad, was also active as
                        a copyist of works of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/John-Chrysostom">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/573">John
                            Chrysostom</persName>
                        </ref> (including one of his writings to the fallen
                            Theodore [<hi rend="italic">
                            <abbr>CPG</abbr>
                        </hi> 4305] and the Letters to Olympias
                            [<hi rend="italic">
                            <abbr>CPG</abbr>
                        </hi> 4405]) and <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Theodore-of-Mopsuestia">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/780">Theodore
                            of Mopsuestia</persName>
                        </ref>. Following Krüger, the fragments of the commentary
                        on <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Mark-the-Monk">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/619">Mark the Monk</persName>
                        </ref>, preserved in <abbr>ms.</abbr> Brit. Libr. Syr. Add. <choice>
                     <reg>17,270</reg>
                     <orig>17270</orig>
                  </choice>,
                        which according to the <hi rend="italic">Catalogue</hi> of W. Wright (<choice>
                            <sic>
                                <hi rend="italic">Catalogue … British Museum</hi>
                            </sic>
                            <corr>
                                <hi rend="italic">Catalogue<choice>
                                        <sic>…</sic>
                                        <corr> … </corr>
                                    </choice>British Museum</hi>
                            </corr>
                        </choice>, vol. 2, 482) may have
                        been written by Abraham bar Dashandad, are rather to be attributed to <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Babai-the-Great">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/359">Babai
                            the Great</persName>
                        </ref>. The Book of Admonition is partly preserved in an Arabic
                        translation in <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Eliya-of-Nisibis">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/472">Eliya of
                            Nisibis</persName>
                        </ref>’s ‘<hi rend="italic">Book of Continence</hi>’.</p>
                </div>
